{"title_page": "Peptide vaccine", "text_new": "A '''peptide vaccine''' is any [[peptide]] which serves to [[immunization|immunize]] an [[organism]] against a [[pathogen]]. Peptide [[Synthetic vaccine|vaccines are often synthetic]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Patarroyo|first=Manuel Elkin|date=1990|title=Studies in owl monkeys leading to the development of a synthetic vaccine against the asexual blood stages of Plasmodium falciparum.|url=http://www.ajtmh.org|journal=American Journal of Tropical Medicine and Hygiene|volume=43,4|pages=339-354|doi=https://doi.org/10.4269/ajtmh.1990.43.339|via=http://www.ajtmh.org/content/journals/10.4269/ajtmh.1990.43.339}}</ref> and [[Protein mimetic|mimic]] naturally occurring proteins from pathogens.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.who.int/biologicals/vaccines/synthetic_peptide_vaccines/en/|title=Synthetic peptide vaccines|publisher=[[World Health Organization]]|access-date=24 July 2015}}</ref> In addition to infectious pathogens, peptide vaccines can be utilized as therapeutic cancer vaccines, where peptides from tumor associated antigens are used to induce effective anti-tumor T cell response. Synthetic long peptides (SLP) have shown promising successful results. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Melief|first=Cornelis J.M.|last2=van der Burg|first2=Sjoerd H.|date=May 2008|title=Immunotherapy of established (pre)malignant disease by synthetic long peptide vaccines|journal=Nature Reviews Cancer|language=En|volume=8|issue=5|pages=351\u2013360|doi=10.1038/nrc2373|pmid=18418403|issn=1474-175X}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Vaccines}}\n\n[[Category:Peptide vaccines| ]]\n\n\n{{vaccine-stub}}\n", "text_old": "A '''peptide vaccine''' is any [[peptide]] which serves to [[immunization|immunize]] an [[organism]] against a [[pathogen]]. Peptide vaccines are often synthetic and [[Protein mimetic|mimic]] naturally occurring proteins from pathogens.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.who.int/biologicals/vaccines/synthetic_peptide_vaccines/en/|title=Synthetic peptide vaccines|publisher=[[World Health Organization]]|access-date=24 July 2015}}</ref> In addition to infectious pathogens, peptide vaccines can be utilized as therapeutic cancer vaccines, where peptides from tumor associated antigens are used to induce effective anti-tumor T cell response. Synthetic long peptides (SLP) have shown promising successful results. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Melief|first=Cornelis J.M.|last2=van der Burg|first2=Sjoerd H.|date=May 2008|title=Immunotherapy of established (pre)malignant disease by synthetic long peptide vaccines|journal=Nature Reviews Cancer|language=En|volume=8|issue=5|pages=351\u2013360|doi=10.1038/nrc2373|pmid=18418403|issn=1474-175X}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Vaccines}}\n\n[[Category:Peptide vaccines| ]]\n\n\n{{vaccine-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lordtree2", "label": "safe", "comment": "added bibliography, linked to article on synthetic vaccines", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peptide_vaccine"}
{"title_page": "SoHyun Bae", "text_new": "{{short description|American painter (b. 1967)}}\n'''SoHyun Bae''' (born 1967) is an American painter<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nyc-arts.org/events/0/sohyun-bae|title=SoHyun Bae|website=NYC-ARTS|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&scope=site&db=nlebk&db=nlabk&AN=1084706|title=South Korea's education exodus: the life and times of early study abroad|last=Lo|first=Adrienne|date=2015|isbn=9780295806525|language=English|oclc=973147808}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Quasha|first=George|title=Art is: speaking portraits in the performative indicative : a work|date=2003|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/art-is-speaking-portraits-in-the-performative-indicative-a-work/oclc/320855278|language=English|oclc=320855278|access-date=2019-07-12|last2=Shambam|first2=David}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/25/arts/dance/google-martha-graham-dance-company.html|title=In the Dance Lab With Martha Graham|last=Kourlas|first=Gia|date=2018-05-25|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-12|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> living and working in [[New York City|New York]]. Her iconography has been described as being shaped by \"a history lived from afar, therefore colored by the absence/presence of memory, doubts of otherness, longing, mythologizing and an awareness of archetypal belonging.\u201d<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/sublimal-icons-sohyun-bae-and-traditional-korean-art-in-context-november-4-23-2011/oclc/913909326|title=Sublimal icons: Sohyun Bae and traditional Korean art in context : November 4-23, 2011|last=Bae|first=Sohyun|last2=Diacono|first2=Mario|last3=Kang Collection|date=2011|publisher=Kang Contemporary|location=New York|language=English|oclc=913909326}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nSoHyun Bae received a [[Bachelor of Fine Arts]] from the [[Rhode Island School of Design]] in 1990 having spent her senior year abroad in [[Rome]], Italy in the European Honors Program, a Master of Fine Arts from [[Boston University College of Fine Arts|Boston University]] in 1994, and a Master of Theological Studies from [[Harvard Divinity School]] in 1997.\n\n==Life==\n{{BLP refimprove|section|date=October 2019}}\nSoHyun Bae was born in Seoul, [[Korea]] to Jongwoo Bae, an Editor/Producer of Donga Broadcasting [[The Dong-a Ilbo|network]] and Hyunye Cho, an essayist and an author of children\u2019s books. Her father\u2019s protest against censorship by Park Chung-hee\u2019s dictatorial regime<ref>{{Citation|title=\ub3d9\uc544\uc77c\ubcf4 \ubc31\uc9c0 \uad11\uace0 \uc0ac\ud0dc|date=2018-11-14|url=https://ko.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=%EB%8F%99%EC%95%84%EC%9D%BC%EB%B3%B4_%EB%B0%B1%EC%A7%80_%EA%B4%91%EA%B3%A0_%EC%82%AC%ED%83%9C&oldid=23010031|work=\uc704\ud0a4\ubc31\uacfc, \uc6b0\ub9ac \ubaa8\ub450\uc758 \ubc31\uacfc\uc0ac\uc804|language=ko|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref> was the reason why her family came to the United States. He was a leading figure in the Donga Ilbo Blank Advertisement Incident (Donga Ilbo Baekji Gwang-go Satae). She was eight years old when her family immigrated to the United States.\n\nEarly influences were: [[Pak Tu-jin]], a Korean poet; [[John Walker (painter)|John Walker]], a British painter; [[Elie Wiesel]], a writer and [[Nobel Laureate|Nobel laureate]]; and [[H. Richard Niebuhr|Richard Nieburh]], Hollis Professor of Divinity at Harvard University.\n\nSoHyun Bae moved to New York in 1997 where she met and worked with: [[Karel Appel]], painter and a founding member of the [[COBRA (avant-garde movement)|Cobra Movement]]; and [[Esteban Vicente]], a first generation [[Abstract expressionism|Abstract Expressionist]]. In the years she lived abroad in [[Bologna]], Italy (2003 - 2009), she met and befriended [[Vasco Bendini]], a painter and a founding member of [[Arte Informale]].\n\n==Awards==\nSoHyun Bae is the recipient of numerous awards including: [[John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation|The John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation]] Fellowship<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gf.org/fellows/all-fellows/sohyun-bae/|title=John Simon Guggenheim Foundation {{!}} SoHyun Bae|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref> in Fine Arts<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nyc-arts.org/events/0/sohyun-bae|title=SoHyun Bae|website=NYC-ARTS|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-12}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/908892018 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/906281767 cite #1 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> Art 2007; [[New York Foundation for the Arts|The New York Foundation for the Arts]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/NYFA_WebAssets/Pictures/fbff420f-79fe-4f34-800a-f94a82fa5876.pdf|title=New York Foundation for the Arts|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=}}</ref> Fellowship in the field of [[Painting]], 2002; The [[Pollock-Krasner Foundation]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pkf-imagecollection.org/artist/SoHyun_Bae/?%20list_url=/artists?sort=AE&page=1&letter=B|title=SoHyun Bae {{!}} Works {{!}} Pollock Krasner Image Collection|website=www.pkf-imagecollection.org|language=en|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref>, Inc. Grant, 2000; a Fellowship at [[Montalvo Arts Center|Montalvo Art Center]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://montalvoarts.org/|title=Montalvo Arts Center {{!}} Welcome|website=montalvoarts.org|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref>, 2019, a Fellowship at The Corporation of [[Yaddo]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yaddo.org/artists/artist-guests/visual-artists/|title=Visual Artists|date=2016-09-11|website=Yaddo|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref>, 2000; [[National Endowment for the Arts|The National Endowment for the Arts]] Fellowship<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/NYFA_WebAssets/Pictures/fbff420f-79fe-4f34-800a-f94a82fa5876.pdf|title=NYFA|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=}}</ref> in conjunction with Virginia Center for Creative Arts<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vcca.com/|title=Virginia Center for the Creative Arts|website=VCCA|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref>, 1996; and a full scholarship<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skowheganart.org/alumni-search|title=Alumni & Faculty Database|website=Skowhegan School of Painting & Sculpture|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref> to the [[Skowhegan School of Painting and Sculpture]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skowheganart.org/|title=Skowhegan School of Painting & Sculpture|website=Skowhegan School of Painting & Sculpture|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref>, 1993. \n\n==Exhibitions==\nHer works have been exhibited world wide in numerous galleries<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/concurrence-divergence-three-korean-women-painters-wonsook-kim-sohyun-bae-chagsoon-oh/oclc/226317082|title=Concurrence divergence: three Korean women painters, Wonsook Kim, Sohyun Bae, Chagsoon Oh.|last=Kang Collection|last2=Kim|first2=W\u014fn-suk|last3=Bae|first3=Sohyun|last4=Oh|first4=Changsoon|date=2007|publisher=Kang Collection Korean Art|location=New York|language=English|oclc=226317082}}</ref>, auction houses and museums<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://searchcollection.asianart.org/start/notFound;jsessionid=43740D706C7A6EC7CF937A762E26C8C5?t:state:flow=b73563d0-e32f-4086-990a-c54a9b757bbe|title=Asian Art Museum Online Collection|website=searchcollection.asianart.org|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref> including the [[Asian Art Museum of San Francisco]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wwwhk.aaa.org.hk/en/collection/search/library/contemporary-korean-artists-in-new-york|title=Contemporary Korean Artists in New York|last=Archive|first=Asia Art|website=wwwhk.aaa.org.hk|language=en|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref>; [[Peabody Museum of Archaeology and Ethnology|Peabody Museum of Archaeology and Ethnology at Harvard University]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.peabody.harvard.edu/node/287|title=Day of the Dead/Dia de los Muertos {{!}} Peabody Museum|website=www.peabody.harvard.edu|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref>; [[Seoul Arts Center]] Hangaram Museum<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.visitseoul.net/attractions/Hangaram-Art-Museum_/4326|title=Visit Seoul - Hangaram Art Museum|website=english.visitseoul.net|language=en|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref>; [[National Museum of Visual Arts (Uruguay)|Museo Nacional di Visual Artes, Montevideo]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mnav.gub.uy/cms.php?e=tripleluz2009|title=Museo Nacional de Artes Visuales|website=mnav.gub.uy|language=es|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref>; [[Queens Museum]], [[Sotheby's|Sotheby\u2019s]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/american-paintings-drawings-sculpture/oclc/890648960|title=American paintings, drawings & sculpture.|last=Sotheby's (Firm)|date=2014|language=English|oclc=890648960}}</ref> NY, and [[Phillips de Pury|Philips de Pury & Luxembourg.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jaygrimm.com/bulletin/2018/4/10/sohyun-bae-paintings-at-450-park-avenue-opens-april-25|title=SoHyun Bae Paintings at 450 Park Avenue Opens April 25|website=Jay Grimm \u2014 Art Advisory|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref> \n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bae, Sohyun}}\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century American painters]]\n[[Category:American women painters]]\n[[Category:Rhode Island School of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:Boston University College of Fine Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Divinity School alumni]]\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:South Korean emigrants to the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American painter (b. 1967)}}\n'''SoHyun Bae''' (born 1967) is an American painter<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nyc-arts.org/events/0/sohyun-bae|title=SoHyun Bae|website=NYC-ARTS|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|ur