as born in Seoul, [[Korea]] to Jongwoo Bae, an Editor/Producer of Donga Broadcasting [[The Dong-a Ilbo|network]] and Hyunye Cho, an essayist and an author of children\u2019s books. Her father\u2019s protest against censorship by Park Chung-hee\u2019s dictatorial regime<ref>{{Citation|title=\ub3d9\uc544\uc77c\ubcf4 \ubc31\uc9c0 \uad11\uace0 \uc0ac\ud0dc|date=2018-11-14|url=https://ko.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=%EB%8F%99%EC%95%84%EC%9D%BC%EB%B3%B4_%EB%B0%B1%EC%A7%80_%EA%B4%91%EA%B3%A0_%EC%82%AC%ED%83%9C&oldid=23010031|work=\uc704\ud0a4\ubc31\uacfc, \uc6b0\ub9ac \ubaa8\ub450\uc758 \ubc31\uacfc\uc0ac\uc804|language=ko|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref> was the reason why her family came to the United States. He was a leading figure in the Donga Ilbo Blank Advertisement Incident (Donga Ilbo Baekji Gwang-go Satae). She was eight years old when her family immigrated to the United States.\n\nEarly influences were: [[Pak Tu-jin]], a Korean poet; [[John Walker (painter)|John Walker]], a British painter; [[Elie Wiesel]], a writer and [[Nobel Laureate|Nobel laureate]]; and [[H. Richard Niebuhr|Richard Nieburh]], Hollis Professor of Divinity at Harvard University.\n\nSoHyun Bae moved to New York in 1997 where she met and worked with: [[Karel Appel]], painter and a founding member of the [[COBRA (avant-garde movement)|Cobra Movement]]; and [[Esteban Vicente]], a first generation [[Abstract expressionism|Abstract Expressionist]]. In the years she lived abroad in [[Bologna]], Italy (2003 - 2009), she met and befriended [[Vasco Bendini]], a painter and a founding member of [[Arte Informale]].\n\n==Awards==\nSoHyun Bae is the recipient of numerous awards including: [[John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation|The John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation]] Fellowship<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gf.org/fellows/all-fellows/sohyun-bae/|title=John Simon Guggenheim Foundation {{!}} SoHyun Bae|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref> in Fine Arts<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nyc-